 {"id":"bd-ybj.3","title":"Add StaleCleanup suggestion type to suggest module","description":"Go has SuggestionStaleCleanup for issues >90 days stale with low engagement. Rust SuggestionType enum missing it. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Add StaleCleanup to SuggestionType in src/analysis/suggest.rs. (2) stale_cleanup_detector(): updated_at >90d, open status, no recent comments, low PageRank. (3) Wire into suggest pipeline. (4) Support --suggest-type stale filter. ACCEPTANCE: --robot-suggest includes StaleCleanup suggestions.","status":"closed","priority":3,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.526260050Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T01:08:26.348227759Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T01:08:26.344589115Z","close_reason":"Implemented StaleCleanup suggestion type: detect_stale_cleanup() finds open issues >90 days stale with low PageRank, generates cleanup suggestions with action commands. 4 unit tests added, all 710 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.526260050Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":17,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/suggest.go — StaleCleanup suggests closing issues that are old, have no recent activity, and have low graph centrality. Currently Rust has SplitLargeComponent, MergeSmallClusters, BreakCycle, AddLabels but not StaleCleanup. Low complexity, high value — helps keep issue graphs clean.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:29Z"},{"id":73,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.3","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.4","title":"Implement WhatIf analysis module for scenario planning","description":"Go's whatif.go computes 'what if we completed this issue' deltas: direct_unblocks (issues immediately unblocked), transitive_unblocks (total downstream unblocks), estimated_days_saved, pagerank_delta (how graph centrality shifts), metric_changes. This powers the top_what_ifs robot output and helps agents identify highest-leverage items. IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Create src/analysis/whatif.rs module. (2) WhatIfDelta struct: issue_id, direct_unblocks (Vec<String>), transitive_unblocks (Vec<String>), estimated_days_saved (f64), pagerank_delta (f64). (3) compute_what_if(graph, issue_id) -> WhatIfDelta: simulate removing the issue from the graph, recompute metrics on the modified graph, diff results. (4) top_what_if_deltas(graph, issues, top_n) -> Vec<WhatIfDelta>: compute for all open issues, sort by transitive_unblocks desc. (5) Wire into Analyzer. Go ref: whatif.go WhatIfDelta, ComputeWhatIfDelta(), TopWhatIfDeltas(). ACCEPTANCE: Analyzer.what_if(issue_id) returns meaningful deltas. Top-5 what-ifs match Go's ranking for reference fixtures.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.680915022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-09T00:01:05.755264756Z","closed_at":"2026-03-09T00:01:05.750323763Z","close_reason":"Implemented WhatIf analysis module (src/analysis/whatif.rs) with WhatIfDelta struct (direct_unblocks, transitive_unblocks, estimated_days_saved, pagerank_delta, cycles_broken). compute_what_if() simulates issue completion by rebuilding graph and diffing metrics. top_what_if_deltas() ranks all open issues by impact. Wired into Analyzer with what_if() and top_what_ifs() methods. 11 unit tests including chain, cycle, empty, single-node, large-graph (100 nodes). 696 tests pass.","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.680915022Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":18,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/whatif.go — WhatIf takes a proposed action (close issue X, add dependency X→Y, remove label Z) and returns the delta in all graph metrics. Implementation: clone the graph, apply the mutation, recompute metrics, diff against baseline. Cache (bd-4h6) makes this fast by avoiding full recomputation when only one node changes.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:38Z"},{"id":74,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.4","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:15Z"}]}
 {"id":"bd-ybj.5","title":"Implement advanced insights: TopKSet, CoverageSet, KPaths, CycleBreak, ParallelCut, ParallelGain","description":"Go's advanced_insights.go (~700 lines) provides sophisticated graph optimization algorithms: (1) TopKSet: K items that maximize downstream unlocks using greedy submodular optimization. (2) CoverageSet: minimal set of items covering all critical paths (vertex cover approximation). (3) KPaths: K-shortest critical paths through the dependency graph (Yen's algorithm). (4) ParallelCut: edges to remove for maximum parallelization (min-cut variant). (5) CycleBreak: suggested edges to break cycles with minimal collateral damage (from Go's bv-graph-wasm cycle_break_suggestions). IMPLEMENTATION: (1) Create src/analysis/advanced.rs. (2) TopKSet: greedy set-cover algorithm over transitive_unblocks. (3) CoverageSet: greedy vertex cover on critical path DAG. (4) KPaths: BFS/DFS-based K-shortest paths using the critical_path infrastructure. (5) CycleBreak: port from Go's cycle_break_suggestions (already in bv-graph-wasm/cycles.rs). (6) AdvancedInsights struct aggregating all results. (7) Wire into Analyzer.advanced_insights(). Go ref: advanced_insights.go. ACCEPTANCE: Unit tests for each algorithm. Results appear in --robot-insights when computed.","status":"closed","priority":2,"issue_type":"task","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.931634610Z","created_by":"ubuntu","updated_at":"2026-03-08T22:44:15.503808231Z","closed_at":"2026-03-08T22:44:15.503789345Z","close_reason":"Implemented 6 advanced insight algorithms (TopKSet, CoverageSet, KPaths, CycleBreak, ParallelCut, ParallelGain) in src/analysis/advanced.rs with 15 unit tests, all passing","source_repo":".","compaction_level":0,"original_size":0,"dependencies":[{"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","depends_on_id":"bd-ybj","type":"parent-child","created_at":"2026-03-07T23:56:38.931634610Z","created_by":"ubuntu","metadata":"{}","thread_id":""}],"comments":[{"id":19,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"Go reference: pkg/analysis/advanced.go — Four advanced analysis types: (1) TopKSet: nodes appearing in top-K across multiple metrics simultaneously (the 'keystone' issues). (2) CoverageSet: greedy minimum set that touches all clusters (for maximum impact work). (3) KPaths: k-shortest paths between specified nodes using Yen's algorithm. (4) CycleBreak: minimum feedback arc set to break all cycles (NP-hard, use greedy approximation). All four use petgraph algorithms.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:06:45Z"},{"id":54,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"CORRECTION: Previous description listed only 4 advanced insight types but Go has 6. The full AdvancedInsights struct from advanced_insights.go lines 58-84 contains: TopKSet (submodular selection for max unlock), CoverageSet (greedy vertex cover), KPaths (k-shortest critical paths), CycleBreak (minimum feedback arc set), PLUS two additional types: ParallelCut (parallel cut analysis) and ParallelGain (parallel gain analysis). The Rust implementation must include all 6 types. The AdvancedInsightsConfig and UsageHints fields must also be included.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:33:14Z"},{"id":75,"issue_id":"bd-ybj.5","author":"Dicklesworthstone","text":"TESTING REQUIREMENT: This task is NOT complete until it includes inline unit tests with deterministic graph fixtures. Tests must cover: (1) happy path with known expected values, (2) empty graph edge case, (3) single-node graph, (4) large graph (100+ nodes) for correctness. Use assert!((actual - expected).abs() < 1e-6) for float comparisons.","created_at":"2026-03-08T00:37:16Z"}]}
